                            <comment id="18643" author="robh" created="Mon, 17 Jul 2006 23:51:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Andreas,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We decided to leave the methods as public for now to maintain backward compatibility. These methods are nor harmful being public so hopefully this isn&apos;t too big an issue. I updated the JavaDoc as appropriate.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Rob&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="18649" author="asenft" created="Tue, 18 Jul 2006 01:40:49 +0000"  >
&lt;p&gt;Hello Rob,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I agree that this is no big issue, it is just an &quot;itch&quot; in a otherwise fine solution. As documented, hopefully not many people relying on the public methods and those who do could make them public again in their subclasses. The other way around people will always presented with actually internal methods by their IDE&apos;s code completion.&lt;br/&gt;
I understand the compatibility concerns, though I wonder what you mean when you say to leave it &quot;by now&quot;. I guess when passing from 1.x to 2.x doesn&apos;t seem a fitting occasion, then there won&apos;t be any better &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/images/icons/emoticons/wink.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, thanks for having a look at it and keeping the docs in sync with the code.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Regards,&lt;br/&gt;
Andreas&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
